<div id="review_2844067370" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2844067370" />
    <a title="Artemis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18622356-artemis"><img alt="Artemis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591520208p2/18622356.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2844067370?book_show_action=true">Jun 02, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Artemis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Artemis" href="/user/show/18622356-artemis">Artemis</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2844067370" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17857085573182700487">I always find it hard to accurately appraise books whose protagonists I hate. Both Jaromil and his mother are small and odious, and my distaste is magnified by the fact that Jaromil is a character whom, if portrayed through a different narratorial lens, I likely would have loved. That’s the point of this book, though, a biting and deeply effective critique of the lyrical poet — and often Kundera seamlessly transitions into speaking of Hugo and Rimbaud and Pushkin in the same breath (and indeed l</span>
  <span id="freeText17857085573182700487" style="display:none">I always find it hard to accurately appraise books whose protagonists I hate. Both Jaromil and his mother are small and odious, and my distaste is magnified by the fact that Jaromil is a character whom, if portrayed through a different narratorial lens, I likely would have loved. That’s the point of this book, though, a biting and deeply effective critique of the lyrical poet — and often Kundera seamlessly transitions into speaking of Hugo and Rimbaud and Pushkin in the same breath (and indeed literally in the same sentence) as his descriptions of Jaromil. The reality probably lies somewhere in the middle of the more familiar exultations of poesy and this unsympathetic critique, although since the former are so commonplace the latter deserves appreciation. Kundera’s judgement of poetry as immaturity, and of the poet’s absolutism as the desperate wish to return back to the monism of the womb, is compelling. His deeply Freudian worldview is obviously compelling to me, but I feel that his characters are *too* Freudian, in the sense that their entire personality seems utterly determined by external (and stereotypically Freudian) sources (in a way that almost makes them caricatures). Which is not to accuse this book of being simplistic - far from that - but it is a qualm I have with the protagonists. <br /><br />Highlights include: <br />“The story of two people about to become lovers is so eternal that it almost made us forget History. How pleasant it is to recount such love stories! How sweet it would be to forget the monster that saps our brief lives as cement for its vain monuments. How sweet it would be to forget History!” <br /><br />“Maman had nothing but contempt for her brother-in-law, ever since she had heard him declare that Voltaire was a physicist who invented volts” LMAO<br /><br />“You think that just because it’s already happened, the past is finished and unchangeable? Oh no, the past is cloaked in a multicolored taffeta and every time we look at it we see a different hue.”<br /><br />Also! Apparently the scene in which Marius gets angry at Cosette because she accidentally exposed her ankle in public while holding her skirt is based on a real incidence between Hugo and his lover and he angrily rebuked her for showing her ankle in one of their letter exchanges .... LOL</span>
  <a data-text-id="17857085573182700487" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


