<div id="review_594662467" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/594662467" />
    <a title="Blake" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9875910-blake"><img alt="Blake" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1508355867p2/9875910.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/594662467?book_show_action=true">Apr 19, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Blake" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Blake" href="/user/show/9875910-blake">Blake</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9875910-blake?shelf=postmodern">postmodern</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer594662467" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4460148027409014601">For me this a really well written, awful book. I feel like Kundera wasted his considerable talents tackling the issues of adolescent male sex anxiety and wanting-to-be-an-adult-already and created the whiniest, most self-centered worm of a protagonist I&apos;ve read. He&apos;s investigations into the nature and purpose of poetry and the life of a poet are good, and his descriptions of interior life are superb, but both are too few and far between to make up for the whole. Even if the Poet were likable in </span>
  <span id="freeText4460148027409014601" style="display:none">For me this a really well written, awful book. I feel like Kundera wasted his considerable talents tackling the issues of adolescent male sex anxiety and wanting-to-be-an-adult-already and created the whiniest, most self-centered worm of a protagonist I've read. He's investigations into the nature and purpose of poetry and the life of a poet are good, and his descriptions of interior life are superb, but both are too few and far between to make up for the whole. Even if the Poet were likable in some way, the awkward transition into adulthood from the prospective of a disgruntled, narcissistic beta-male is just lame storytelling. I should mention as a disclaimer that I dislike the entire genre, right down to Catcher in the Rye.<br /><br />That said, the relationship between the protag and his mother, or more specifically, their relationship as seen through her, was absurd enough to be gripping.<br /><br />It was also interesting to see a child of a concentration camp victim making a habit of drawing soldiers with animal faces 12 years before Art Spiegelman inked MAUS and whole alternative lifetimes spent in dreams within dreams within dreams 36 years before the movie Inception came out. The ideas that seem the most original are usually ones that were already out there. Being an artist has more to do with gestalt than original thought. Everyone you think is great is standing on the shoulders of giants.<br /><br />That said, I still think Kundera is a giant. I just think Life is Elsewhere is bilge-water compared to the fine wine of Unbearable Lightness of Being. Read that one instead.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4460148027409014601" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


